\newlabel{tab:mitig:conv}{{9}{12}{Convolution mitigation across the filter family on the A100-SXM4 (optimized implicit-GEMM Triton, FP16; input $32\times 256\times 128\times 128$). $E_\text {lib}$ = library efficiency relative to PyTorch/cuDNN; the mitigation holds 36--76\% across the $1\times 1$--$7\times 7$ filter family, all correct.\relax }{table.caption.43}{}}
\newlabel{tab:mitig:conv@cref}{{[table][9][]9}{[1][12][]12}}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {subsection}{\numberline {7.3}Convolution: Partial Recovery via Implicit GEMM}{12}{subsection.7.3}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{sec:mitig:conv}{{7.3}{12}{Convolution: Partial Recovery via Implicit GEMM}{subsection.7.3}{}}
\newlabel{sec:mitig:conv@cref}{{[subsection][3][7]7.3}{[1][11][]12}}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {paragraph}{Finding: Restructuring Conv2d as an implicit GEMM with FP16 Tensor Core acceleration, input padding to 16-byte alignment (addressing RC1), and an expanded autotune configuration space (addressing RC2) yields a $2.57\times $ latency reduction ($32.1\nonbreakingspace \text  {ms} \to 12.5\nonbreakingspace \text  {ms}$) in the AKO4ALL optimization campaign. On the A100-SXM4, where cuDNN is substantially faster, the same implicit-GEMM restructuring holds 36--76\% of PyTorch/cuDNN efficiency across the $1\times 1$--$7\times 7$ filter family (all correct)--- the gap is narrowed but not closed.}{12}{section*.42}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {subsection}{\numberline {7.4}GEMM and Reduction Kernels}{12}{subsection.7.4}\protected@file@percent }
